We can already see that:

  • sellerRating, Duration, ClosePrice and OpenPrice are numerical variables;
  • Category, currency and endDay are categorical variables made of characters;
  • Competitive? is a dummy variable.

The eBayAuctions.csv file isn’t described at the beginning of exercise 13.2. We will cite here the description which is given in Exercise 9.1. This gives us the context and defines the meaning of each variable.

“The file eBayAuctions.csv contains information on 1972 auctions that transacted on eBay.com during May–June 2004. The goal is to use these data to build a model that will classify auctions as competitive or non-competitive. A competitive auction is defined as an auction with at least two bids placed on the item auctioned. The data include variables that describe the item (auction category), the seller (his/her eBay rating), and the auction terms that the seller selected (auction duration, opening price, currency, day-of-week of auction close). In addition, we have the price at which the auction closed. The task is to predict whether or not the auction will be competitive.”

Now, we plot the distributions of the numerical variables.

eBayAuctions[, c(3,4,6,7)] %>% gather() %>%           # gather transforms data into two columns with
                                                      # "key" and "value"
  ggplot(aes(value)) +                                # plotting the value
  facet_wrap(~ key, scales = "free") +                # making one plot for each key with facet
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "#FA8072") + # making histograms
  theme_light() +                                     # aesthetic theme for our plots
  labs(x = "Variables distributions", y = "",         # label of the figure
       title = "Numerical variables distributions")

We can immediately see that sellerRating, OpenPrice and ClosePrice seem very skewed. Duration does not. We use skewness() from the e1071 package to check the skewness index of our four numerical variables.

We recall the criteria for the skewness index:

  • Around 0: variable is symmetrical;
  • Above 0.5 in absolute value: variable is moderately skewed;
  • Above 1 in absolute value: variable is highly skewed.
# sapply() allows to use skewness() on multiple columns of our data
sapply(eBayAuctions[, c(3,4,6,7)], skewness)
## sellerRating     Duration   ClosePrice    OpenPrice 
##   3.21378117  -0.06321583   6.04803637  13.51295100

As we supposed, Duration isn’t skewed. However, the other three are all highly skewed!

We will transform them.

# sellerRating had the lowest skewness index among the three, a 4th root is sufficient here
eBayAuctions$sellerRating <- eBayAuctions$sellerRating^(1/4)
# for ClosePrice and OpenPrice which are more skewed, we use the logarithm
# we add 1 to the values so the values remain positive (min of both variables is 0.1)
eBayAuctions$ClosePrice <- log(eBayAuctions$ClosePrice+1)
eBayAuctions$OpenPrice <- log(eBayAuctions$OpenPrice+1)

# we compute the skewness to see how it has evolved
sapply(eBayAuctions[, c(3,4,6,7)], skewness)
## sellerRating     Duration   ClosePrice    OpenPrice 
##   0.47876332  -0.06321583   0.64180830   0.69164878

The skewness indexes are much better now! Our variables aren’t perfectly symmetrical, but they aren’t highly skewed anymore.

We plot the new distributions.

Now, we will partition our data into training and validation sets.

# set seed for reproducing the partition
set.seed(111)

# generating training set index
train.index <- sample(c(1:nrow(eBayAuctions)), 0.6*nrow(eBayAuctions))
# generating validation set index as the complementary of training set
valid.index <- setdiff(c(1:nrow(eBayAuctions)), train.index)

# creating data tables Train and Valid using the indexes
Train <- eBayAuctions[train.index, ]
Valid <- eBayAuctions[valid.index, ]

# removing indexes as they aren't used anymore
rm(train.index, valid.index)

1 Run a classification tree, using the default controls of rpart().

We run the classification tree and plot it.

# running the classification tree using the class method on training data
Tree <- rpart(Competitive ~ . , data = Train, method = "class")

# plotting the tree
prp(Tree, type = 1,                                                 # labels all nodes
    extra = 1,                                                      # displays n = ...
    varlen = -16,                                                   # number of chars of variables
    under = TRUE,                                                   # n = ... appears under node
    digits = -1,                                                    # avoid scientific notation
    box.col=ifelse(Tree$frame$var == "<leaf>", '#FA8072', 'white')) # coloring leaves in pink

We compute the confusion matrix on the validation set.

# we first need the predictions of the validation set using the tree
# we create a data table in which we will store all predictions
Predictions = data.table(PredTree = predict(Tree, Valid, type = "class"))

# computing the confusion matrix (function is from caret package)
CMTree <- confusionMatrix(Predictions$PredTree, Valid$Competitive, positive = "1")
CMTree

We display the lift and decile charts.

# computing the probabilities of validation set
ProbTree <- predict(Tree, Valid, type = "prob")
# we only select the 2nd column (probabilities for Competitive = 1)
ProbTree <- ProbTree[, 2]
# we need the values of Competitive as numeric instead of factor, we convert them
lift.decile.chart(ProbTree, as.numeric(Valid$Competitive)-1, type = "lift")

lift.decile.chart(ProbTree, as.numeric(Valid$Competitive)-1, type = "decile")

# we store ProbTree inside Predictions and remove it from our environment afterwards
Predictions <- Predictions[, ProbTree := ProbTree]
rm(ProbTree)

The lift of the first decile is of 1.76. This means that the mean response is equal to 1.76 times the mean response we would have taking cases at random.

2 Run a boosted tree with the same predictors (use function boosting() in the adabag package).

TreeBoosted <- boosting(Competitive ~ . , data = Train)

We compute the confusion matrix of the validation set.

# we first need the predictions of the validation set using boosting

4 Run a random forest (use function randomForest() in package randomForest with argument mtry = 4).

We run the random forest.

RandomForest <- randomForest(Competitive ~ . , data = Train, mtry = 4)

We compute the confusion matrix for the random forest.

# we add the predicted classes to Prediction
Predictions[, RFPred := predict(RandomForest, Valid, type = "class")]
# we compute the predicted probabilities
RFProb <- predict(RandomForest, Valid, type = "prob")
# we add the predicted probabilities for class 1 (2nd column) to Predictions
Predictions[, RFProb := RFProb[, 2]]
# we remove the object now that it is stored inside predictions
rm(RFProb)
# we compute the confusion matrix
CMRF <- confusionMatrix(Predictions$RFPred, Valid$Competitive, positive = "1")

We compute the lift and decile charts for our random forest.

lift.decile.chart(Predictions$RFProb, as.numeric(Valid$Competitive)-1, type = "lift")

lift.decile.chart(Predictions$RFProb, as.numeric(Valid$Competitive)-1, type = "decile")

Again, the lift of the first decile is identical to the ones of boosting and bagging. We can note that the fifth decile has a lift of 0.40, which is better than bagging (and, of course, the default tree) but lower than boosting at 0.53.

Overall, the random forest performs better than the bagged tree. The two methods are conceptually very close, but there is one difference.

Bagging consists in:

  1. From the validation set, generating a certain number \(N\) of samples with the same size as Valid (repetition is allowed);
  2. Running a tree on our \(N\) samples;
  3. Determining the class of each record in Valid by a majority vote on the \(N\) samples.

Random forests follow the same process but with an additional twist. At each split of each tree, instead of choosing from all the predictors, the next split is chosen from a sample of some of the predictors. Here, the parameter mtry controls how many variables are in the sample (so in our case, it was four predictor variables).

This difference is important as it means that unlike in bagging, where we produced \(N\) copies of the same tree, in random forests, each tree will be different, as the splits won’t be made on the same variables from one tree to another. Hence the name random forest!
